        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         <strong>
          2022
         </strong>
         <strong>
          is the year that web3 starts making a meaningful impact on atoms-based challenges like healthcare and climate
         </strong>
         .
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Thus far, web3 has been focused on
         <strong>
          bits
         </strong>
         , on creating a user-owned internet by infusing physical properties like scarcity, uniqueness, ownership, and self-custody into digital items. That\xe2\x80\x99s an important track; as more of our time, money, relationships, and work goes digital, it\xe2\x80\x99s important that we have the right to own as well as rent.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         But all of the wild shit in web3 also serves another purpose. In the immortal words of Allen Iverson\xe2\x80\xa6
        </p>
        <div class="captioned-image-container-static" style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin-bottom: 16px; text-align: center;">
         <figure style="display: inline-block; margin: 0 auto; width: 100%;">
