        </div>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         The fact that these are high-price but ultimately low-stakes (the world won\xe2\x80\x99t end if the Bored Ape Yacht Club disappeared) projects is a feature, not a bug. These projects combine internet iteration speed with real-world-huge sums of money to let humanity speed-run simulations on group coordination, all while picking up specific tools to help address hard problems.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         From Squiggles to a cure for cancer, Apes to carbon reduction, Punks to saving the fishes.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         That\xe2\x80\x99s a big leap. How\xe2\x80\x99d I get here?
        </p>
        <h3 style="-moz-osx-font-smoothing: antialiased; -webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased; color: #1a1a1a; font-family: 'SF Compact Display', -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, 'Segoe UI', Roboto, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif, 'Apple Color Emoji', 'Segoe UI Emoji', 'Segoe UI Symbol'; font-size: 1.375em; font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.16em; margin: 1em 0 0.625em 0;">
         <strong>
          Complexity
         </strong>
        </h3>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Over the break, I
         <a href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkM2OhSAMhZ9GloY_FRYsJpnc3TyDQegocxUM1Lnx7Qevi0kItDSnp_2cRZhTPs2eCpLrGvHcwUR4lRUQIZOjQB6DN6znSnRSE2-kZ6pTJJTxOwNsNqwG8wFkP6Y1OIshxbeCUt6RxSjZCy2cFko5xYSGoWZ8Utx9U6-5uH3t4QNEBwZ-IZ8pAlnNgriXRnw0_FEPvsI1UevSVrPduuf5VYOCFo9SAyYHVtvLXimpOy3F0DXiUfWfnJJgOOWcMiqYpLLjLW-dHaimAKxnMCkHbf-j9eDmpZF0m3lbjqn2ds_LkGQTE04phzjX8nOxG6zvQl16rO92xIDnCNFOK_ibB95Y34TGGSLkituPFitMyThTAxWK63v_Ckxev1RSUp19qqr4b_oHFpWK8A" rel="" style="color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">
          asked people on Twitter
         </a>
         for the one book or essay they\xe2\x80\x99d recommend reading to get ready for the next decade. I wanted to zoom out, think about atoms more than bits for a change, and shake my brain up a little bit.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         <em>
          <a href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFUUuPnDAM_jXkBkpCeB1y6DKdrfZStZW22hMKiQeyAwkKobPTX18zSF3JsuXnZ_vTKsLgw10ufo1kV128LyAd3NYJYoRAthVCZ41kJa_zQjTESGFYXdTErt0lAMzKTjKGDciy9ZPVKlrvHh2U8oKMUheq0LliDWOXuhQ5cFEJrXUBitJeqANXbcaC0yDhD4S7d0AmOca4rEn-JeFnlNvtlqlZ_fUu037GQOvnZYIPG-_p1xnCYN2Q_tKPKen3YCCk7aj8mkLv_RXrzYLqiVa_X1-LF_5zn5qfdbAmyU-n9u3b-eX0_KN9YwkvD1mXABf7gWn9Hyrhxb7QUxwBNXq8Vbjkbplo9qaA9XXKiJWcck4ZzZmgouAZz7SqaEMBWMmgrzVk5XvTVHoYE0HngWfr1q9R6et-IAnS-dj7gGdh-jqqGaZHAv_coZ03h_t04FQ_gTkoiAeTD1K6ARwEZNh0KiJ_gnFWVzSveXO8HDkSe5QKShDZeOxyn6D_AMissIg" rel="" style="color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">
           Complexity: The Emerging Science at the End of Order and Chaos
          </a>
         </em>
         by M. Mitchell Waldrop, won.
        </p>
        <div class="captioned-image-container-static" style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin-bottom: 16px; text-align: center;">
         <figure style="display: inline-block; margin: 0 auto; width: 100%;">
          <table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" class="image-wrapper" style="margin: 8px auto; mso-padding-alt: 1em 0 1.6em;" width="100%">
           <tbody>
            <tr>
             <td style="text-align: center;">
             </td>
             <td align="left" class="content" style="text-align: center;" width="235">
              <a class="image-link" href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxVUsuu3CAM_Zphl4hngEUWV1fqb0Q8nAydBFIg93b69SXJoqqE7IMt-1g-dqbCkvJ73FOp6DRTfe8wRvguK9QKGR0F8hT8SAaqmOAa-ZF7ooRCoUxzBthMWMeaD0D7YdfgTA0pXhUYU4Geo2vAemzlgNngqMDCE-rtPNvZadDk5jWHDxAdjPAF-Z0ioHV81rqXB_t40B_tOR_7cthSjXv1Lm0tFDazQPMzVPc8fWtT04N-_roB-1hS8u0_r9Oe05KhlPAFLV4qwN4qbgoqThJx0jRjD_eCls8dYGGtU7yzxrCOMwmdFkR1xltGLUipFe8L681m_qRovss9V-tx7-KC15DlgjDM1A7SdtoS23EhcGcUZp2jeJ41lcZyOVEmfrdN93tcUBgpphQTzAjHXNCe9s5IrDEAGQhY5aAffmot3fJ8cLwt9L8VoTzGVG3KIS4t_XqaDdYr0eabmt-OGOp7gmjsCv6Wsd7XcAk7LRAhtyvxk6ntBjihREnMFNW3bE1nfkYxx6gx-9Sq4j_Sv-P-xk4" rel="" style="border: none; display: block; height: auto; margin: 0; padding: 0; text-decoration: none; width: auto;" target="_blank">
               <img alt="" class="" data-attrs='{"src":"https://bucketeer-e05bbc84-baa3-437e-9518-adb32be77984.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/e6f2b67b-9b1b-4550-a803-c20ff927ab47_235x354.png","fullscreen":null,"height":354,"width":235,"resizeWidth":null,"bytes":null,"alt":null,"title":null,"type":null,"href":null}' height="354" src="https://cdn.substack.com/image/fetch/w_235,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fbucketeer-e05bbc84-baa3-437e-9518-adb32be77984.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fe6f2b67b-9b1b-4550-a803-c20ff927ab47_235x354.png" style="-ms-interpolation-mode: bicubic; border: none !important; display: block; height: auto; margin: 0 auto; margin-bottom: 0; max-width: 100%; vertical-align: middle; width: auto;" width="235"/>
              </a>
             </td>
             <td style="text-align: center;">
             </td>
            </tr>
           </tbody>
          </table>
         </figure>
        </div>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         On the surface, it\xe2\x80\x99s a funny winner of the \xe2\x80\x9cprepare for the next decade\xe2\x80\x9d contest. Waldrop wrote the book thirty years ago, in 1992. It\xe2\x80\x99s not new enough to be expressly written for the next decade, and not old enough to sit among the timeless classics that work in
         <em>
          any
         </em>
         decade. But the crowds are wise; it was an excellent pick.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         <em>
          Complexity
         </em>
         tells the early history of
         <strong>
          complex systems science
         </strong>
         through the stories of the founders of the
         <a href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkMGOhSAMRb_msTSAqLBgMZv5DYJQlXkKBuoY_354upikaZPbtDfnOoswp3zpPRUkn2bw2kFHOMsKiJDJUSCb4DXruWw7oYjXwjPZSRKKmTLAZsOqMR9A9mNcg7MYUrwvKOUdWTTIQQjVj4NqwU6yvmmdVJNgjgk_Cvr42sMHiA40_EK-UgSy6gVxL6_268W_a53n2RQb0U7QgD-qQoLmlHPKaMsEFR1veOPsQBUFYD2DUTpo-h-lBjcvL0G3mTflGAta925c2kjWMeGYcohzXb8Xu8F6LyqKqXM7YsDLQLTjCv6hxCesm9vMECHXEL2xWCMSjDM50FZy9VDVGMRHpRWzOvtUr-K_6R-u_YBm" rel="" style="color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">
          Santa Fe Institute
         </a>
         <em>
         </em>
         (SFI)
         <em>
          ,
         </em>
         \xe2\x80\x9ca research institute in Santa Fe that is devoted to the study of complexity in all its forms.\xe2\x80\x9d Thirty years later, SFI is still running and complex systems science is still relevant. In October, the
         <a href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkMtuhiAUhJ9GdjWAgLJg0U1fw3A5VforGMAa-_RFTdPkBCYzOUz4rC4wxXSqLeaCrmMs5wYqwJEXKAUS2jOk0TtFBB06ziRyijky8AH5PH4mgFX7RZW0A9p2s3iri4_h3sCYcjSrXhrpDBfckTq9EAMTPecUtGTaGvH06t15CBYUfEM6YwC0qLmULTfde0M_6hzH0YZoYNmS_4E2pqmat86XmM_s7aUopuQvedMhxL0-u0Io1URe1ZhigjvCMOO0pa3VPZYYgAgCZrDQii8pezvNDcPrRNu8m1y0fbU2riipEIuJyYepxq9Zr7DcQf38WO91D76cIwRtFnAPl_LgvUmNEwRIFbsbdalQGaFk6HE3UPlwqODY5WKGUW12sW6F_9JfafySBQ" rel="" style="color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">
          2021 Nobel Prize in Physics
         </a>
         went to three scientists, \xe2\x80\x9cFor
         <strong>
          groundbreaking contributions to our understanding of complex systems
         </strong>
         "
         <em>
         </em>
         used to create more accurate models of the effect of global warming on the climate.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         <strong>
          Complex systems
         </strong>
         are everywhere, from the climate to the human brain to the power grid to the economy to the beginning of life on this planet from the primordial stew of molecules. They\xe2\x80\x99re devilishly hard to capture in models and differential equations, but crucially important to understand.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Before complex systems science, the prevailing approach to understanding these complex systems was
         <strong>
          reductionism:
         </strong>
         breaking them down into their component parts and trying to build a complete picture by adding together each piece. Challenge is, complex systems do all sorts of things that can\xe2\x80\x99t be predicted by looking at each piece. They\xe2\x80\x99re emergent: the whole is greater, and different, than the sum of its parts.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         <em>
          (Incidentally, I think many of the anti-web3 arguments miss by being overly reductionist.\xc2\xa0 I\xe2\x80\x99m actually pretty sure the midwit meme is just reductionism vs. complexity.)
         </em>
        </p>
        <div class="captioned-image-container-static" style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin-bottom: 16px; text-align: center;">
         <figure style="display: inline-block; margin: 0 auto; width: 100%;">
          <table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" class="image-wrapper" style="margin: 8px auto; mso-padding-alt: 1em 0 1.6em;" width="100%">
           <tbody>
            <tr>
             <td style="text-align: center;">
             </td>
             <td align="left" class="content" style="text-align: center;" width="550">
              <a class="image-link" href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxVUsuunDAM_ZphB8oTkgWLqyv1N1AehkkHEpqEezv9-hpYVJUi2zmWz3FiO1NhSfk97qnU5jRTfe8wRvguK9QKuTkK5Cn4kfZMcSl040fhqZKqCWWaM8BmwjrWfECzH3YNztSQ4lVBCJPNc6RKSyrZIHtKNQeqBeG275WaAfFe3brm8AGigxG-IL9ThGYdn7Xu5cE_HuwHHudjVw5bqnGvzqUNobCZBdDPUN3z9EhT04N9_roD_rGk5PE-r9Oe05KhlPAFiJcKsGPFLcHkKSJPGTT2cC_AfG6BSGudEq01hreCD9DiW1RrvOXMwjBoJbrCO7OZPyma73L3hRz3X1zh1WS5QumZYUwzpNKuFc6QFulN66lXwzAL4NpOtCfkt6ai2-PShJERxgglnAoiJOtY58xANAGgPQWrHHT9T60HtzwfgmwL---PmjzGVG3KIS6Yfj3NBuuVwAYn9NsRQ31PEI1dwd9zrPc6XJOdFoiQcU38ZCougaCMqoFwxfQ9Nxy0OFEiSIPKPmFV_Cf6F2agxPo" rel="" style="border: none; display: block; height: auto; margin: 0; padding: 0; text-decoration: none; width: auto;" target="_blank">
               <img alt="" class="" data-attrs='{"src":"https://bucketeer-e05bbc84-baa3-437e-9518-adb32be77984.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/5d2a2292-439c-4ca0-bc8a-d1d877f4e39b_1600x914.png","fullscreen":null,"height":628,"width":1100,"resizeWidth":null,"bytes":null,"alt":null,"title":null,"type":null,"href":null}' height="314" src="https://cdn.substack.com/image/fetch/w_550,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fbucketeer-e05bbc84-baa3-437e-9518-adb32be77984.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F5d2a2292-439c-4ca0-bc8a-d1d877f4e39b_1600x914.png" style="-ms-interpolation-mode: bicubic; border: none !important; display: block; height: auto; margin: 0 auto; margin-bottom: 0; max-width: 100%; vertical-align: middle; width: auto;" width="550"/>
              </a>
             </td>
             <td style="text-align: center;">
             </td>
            </tr>
           </tbody>
          </table>
         </figure>
        </div>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Take economics. The economics that I studied in college, except for one frisky Behavioral Economics course, assumes that \xe2\x80\x9ceconomic man\xe2\x80\x9d is perfectly rational and seeks to fit the economy into a series of differential equations and supply-demand curves on top of those assumptions. It seeks equilibrium. It\xe2\x80\x99s mathematically elegant, all fits together, and\xe2\x80\xa6 is pretty much entirely disconnected from reality.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         The real economy, like most complex systems, doesn\xe2\x80\x99t reach equilibrium. It evolves, based on the actions, rational and irrational, of its billions of individual participants.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Grokking the status quo\xe2\x80\x99s shortcomings, and armed with the heretical idea of increasing returns \xe2\x80\x93 a concept familiar to all of us in tech today but much less accepted in the early 1980s \xe2\x80\x93 Stanford economist Brian Arthur set out to create a new economic framework at Santa Fe.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         The stakes were more than academic. The world was coming out of a painful period of stagflation in the 1970s that called into question the Keynesians\xe2\x80\x99 ability to stabilize the economy. A more realistic economic framework would help policymakers and financiers design interventions that would stimulate growth and employment, stabilize the market, and better achieve the goals of their fiscal and monetary programs.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         So instead of differential equations based on assumptions, Arthur proposed agent-based simulations:
        </p>
        <blockquote style="border-left: 4px solid #67bdfc; margin: 1em 0;">
         <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0; margin-left: 1em;">
          <em>
           I had this notion that you could have within your office in the university
           <strong>
            a little peasant economy developing under a bubble of glass
           </strong>
           . Of course, it would really be in a computer. But it would have to be all these little agents, preprogrammed to get smart and interact with each other.
          </em>
         </p>
         <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0; margin-left: 1em;">
          <em>
           Then in this dreamlike idea, you\xe2\x80\x99d go in one morning and say, \xe2\x80\x98Hey, look at these guys! Two or three weeks ago all they were doing was bartering and now they\xe2\x80\x99ve got joint stock companies.\xe2\x80\x99 Then the next day you\xe2\x80\x99d come in and say, \xe2\x80\x98Oh \xe2\x80\x93 they\xe2\x80\x99ve discovered central banking.\xe2\x80\x99 Then a few days later you\xe2\x80\x99d have all your colleagues clustered around you and you\xe2\x80\x99re peering in: \xe2\x80\x98Wow! They\xe2\x80\x99ve got labor unions! What\xe2\x80\x99ll they think of next?\xe2\x80\x99 Or half of them have gone Communist.
          </em>
         </p>
        </blockquote>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         In practice, there was no Sims-like economic simulation running in Arthur\xe2\x80\x99s office. It was just that, instead of this\xe2\x80\xa6
        </p>
        <div class="captioned-image-container-static" style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin-bottom: 16px; text-align: center;">
         <figure style="display: inline-block; margin: 0 auto; width: 100%;">
          <table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" class="image-wrapper" style="margin: 8px auto; mso-padding-alt: 1em 0 1.6em;" width="100%">
           <tbody>
            <tr>
             <td style="text-align: center;">
             </td>
             <td align="left" class="content" style="text-align: center;" width="550">
              <a class="image-link" href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxVUsuu3CAM_Zphl4hnAgsWV1fqb0Q8nAydBFIg93b69SXJoqqEbGPr-Fg-dqbCkvJb76lUdJqpvnfQEb7LCrVCRkeBPAWvyUAlE1whr7knUkgUyjRngM2EVdd8ANoPuwZnakjxQmBMBXrqkcxWGoWNsliQmRE1E--5nQ0fHCPm5jWHDxAdaPiC_E4R0Kqfte7lwT4e9Ed7zse-HLZU4169S1tLhc0s0PwM1T1P39rU9KCfv-6AfSwp-faf12nPaclQSviCli8VYG-Im4KKk0ScNM3Yw72g1XMHWFjrJO-sMazjbIROCSI74y2jFsZRSd4X1pvN_EnRfJd7rtbj3sUVXkOWKxwHwEph1oGbeceHkbR-1nZqmIWihDJh5TQQ-Vtg2e9xQUFTTCkmmBGOuaA97Z0ZscIAZCBgpYN--KnU6Jbng-Ntof-tCGUdU7Uph7i08utpNlivQptvan47YqjvCaKxK_hbxnpfwyXstECE3K7ET6a2G-CEEjliJqm6ZWs68zOLOUaN2aeGiv9I_wJqAsW2" rel="" style="border: none; display: block; height: auto; margin: 0; padding: 0; text-decoration: none; width: auto;" target="_blank">
               <img alt="" class="" data-attrs='{"src":"https://bucketeer-e05bbc84-baa3-437e-9518-adb32be77984.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/76e09903-ecf4-4671-95bb-96f5921235b8_618x508.png","fullscreen":null,"height":508,"width":618,"resizeWidth":null,"bytes":null,"alt":null,"title":null,"type":null,"href":null}' height="452.10355987055016" src="https://cdn.substack.com/image/fetch/w_550,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fbucketeer-e05bbc84-baa3-437e-9518-adb32be77984.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F76e09903-ecf4-4671-95bb-96f5921235b8_618x508.png" style="-ms-interpolation-mode: bicubic; border: none !important; display: block; height: auto; margin: 0 auto; margin-bottom: 0; max-width: 100%; vertical-align: middle; width: auto;" width="550"/>
              </a>
             </td>
             <td style="text-align: center;">
             </td>
            </tr>
           </tbody>
          </table>
         </figure>
        </div>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Arthur would let the agents in his simulations run wild, resulting in graphs that look like this:
